  "prompt": "What is the resolution of spy satellites?",
  "response": "The resolution of spy satellites can vary significantly based on the specific satellite and its intended purpose. Generally speaking, high-resolution military reconnaissance satellites can achieve ground resolutions ranging from about 30 centimeters (about 1 foot) to several meters. \n\nSome of the most advanced spy satellites, like those used by the United States and other countries, may have capabilities that allow them to discern objects as small as 10 to 25 centimeters, which is sufficient for identifying vehicles, gathering intelligence on military installations, and monitoring other significant developments on the ground.\n\nIt is important to note that specific details about the capabilities and resolutions of military satellites are often classified, so precise information may not be publicly available. Overall, advancements in satellite technology continue to push the boundaries of what is possible in terms of resolution and imaging capabilities.",
